Analysis of Variance (ANOVA-PCA)

We want to evaluate how different these 3 groups are regarding their answers to the questionnaire. However, as we have 35 questions to evaluate, we start by performing a dimensionality reduction with Principal Components Analysis (PCA). From here, we perform an Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) to evaluate the differences among the groups.

Note: we opt to use a parametric test such as ANOVA, considering that PCA results in continuous variables for which we can assume normality.

# Take answers for questions 1 to 35. Execute PCA analysis and show summary.
ds.pca <- ds[12:46]
pca <- prcomp(ds.pca, scale = FALSE)

It can be noted that:

  • both Standard deviation and Proportion of Variance for each component are progressively smaller, showing that each component explains less sample variability than the previous.
  • Cumulative Proportion of Variance accumulates to 1, showing that all components combined fully explain sample variability.


For a cleaner interpretation, letâs evaluate how much sample variance is explained by the first 4 components.

All groups

Letâs execute ANOVA on the different groups, assuming only the first 3 components.

#' Prepare a dataset with strata and PCs 1 to 3, for analysis. Also prepare subsets for each stratum.
ds.test <- data.frame(strata = ds$Stratum,
                      pc1 = pca$x[,1],
                      pc2 = pca$x[,2],
                      pc3 = pca$x[,3])

ds.test.stratum1 <- subset(ds.test, strata == "1.Never notified")
ds.test.stratum2 <- subset(ds.test, strata == "2.Doesn't usually notify")
ds.test.stratum3 <- subset(ds.test, strata == "3.Usually notifies")
#' Test for all 3 strata simultaneously
aov.test.all <- aov(pc1 + pc2 + pc3 ~ strata, 
                    data = ds.test)
summary(aov.test.all)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## strata        2  226.5  113.23   8.283 0.000343 ***
## Residuals   214 2925.5   13.67                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The p-values of 0.000343 (that is, below alpha 0.05) rejects the null hypothesis of all groupsâ means being equal. Therefore, we must conclude that there are statistically significant differences among the 3 groups (p < 0.001). That is, the 3 groups initially defined are not similar between themselves.

Letâs now perform the analysis for only 2 groups at a time.


Group 1 vs 2

#' Test pairs of strata: 1 vs 2 (exclude 3)
#'   - 1.Never notified
#'   - 2.Doesn't usually notify
aov.test.12 <- aov(pc1 + pc2 + pc3 ~ strata, 
                   data = subset(ds.test, strata != "3.Usually notifies"))
summary(aov.test.12)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## strata        1    2.4   2.365   0.167  0.683
## Residuals   173 2451.8  14.172

In this case, the p-values does not rejects null hypothesis. We conclude that there is no significant difference between strata 1 and 2 (p = 0.683). That is, users who never notified (group 1) respond similarly to those who donât usually notify (group 2).


Group 1 vs 3

#' Test pairs of strata: 1 vs 3 (exclude 2)
#'   - 1.Never notified
#'   - 3.Usually notifies 
aov.test.13 <- aov(pc1 + pc2 + pc3 ~ strata, 
                   data = subset(ds.test, strata != "2.Doesn't usually notify"))
summary(aov.test.13)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## strata        1  191.7   191.7   13.79 0.000283 ***
## Residuals   157 2181.6    13.9                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Here, the p-values rejects the null hypothesis, meaning that these groups are indeed different. We conclude that there is a statistical significant difference between strata 1 and 3 (p < 0.001). That is, Non-notifiers (group 1) and Regular-notifiers (group 3) respond differently.


Group 2 vs 3

#' Test pairs of strata: 2 vs 3 (exclude 1)
#'   - 2.Doesn't usually notify
#'   - 3.Usually notifies 
aov.test.23 <- aov(pc1+pc2+pc3 ~ strata, 
                   data = subset(ds.test, strata != "1.Never notified"))
summary(aov.test.23)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## strata       1  182.5  182.52   14.69 0.000224 ***
## Residuals   98 1217.5   12.42                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Also in this case, the p-values rejects null hypothesis showing that these groups are different. We conclude that there is a statistical significant difference between strata 2 and 3 (p < 0.001). That is, Infrequent-notifiers (group 2) and Regular-notifiers (group 3) respond differently.


Conclusion from ANOVA-PCA

From this analysis, we conclude that Non-notifiers (group 1) and Infrequent-notifiers (group 2) responded similarly to the questionnaire (p=0.683). However, Frequent-notifiers (group 3) present respond significantly different answers from the other 2 groups (p<0.001)

Based on this analysis, we can assume that it is meaningless to discriminate groups 1 and 2, for which we can treat these as a single group.



Comparing questionnaire results

We proceed with the analysis to questionnaire results for all 35 questions. Based on previous analysis, we assume 2 different groups:

  • Non-regular notifiers (previously groups 1.Never notified and 2.Doesnât usually notify)
  • Regular notifiers (previously group 3.Usually notifies)

We compare responses of both groups to each question with MannâWhitney U test, considering that Likert scale values are ordinal. P-values < 0.05 suggest that both groups have different attitudes towards the question asked.

Note: here we opt to use a non-parametric test such as MannâWhitney U test, considering that a 5-point likert scale is not a continuous variable but rather an ordinal categorical one. Nonetheless, this interpretation is not universal, with some researchers opting to treat Likert scales as continuous variables.


From the table below it can be noted that for question âQ01. I am familiar with the Portuguese Pharmacovigilance System.â both groups have different attitudes toward this topic (p < 0.001)

In contrast, question âQ07. Pharmacovigilance is an important activity in the drug life cycle.â appears to trigger similar responses between both groups (p = 0.634).

# Define questions to analyse
questions <- 1:35

# Prepare summary statistics for groups 1 and 2 combined
groups_12 <- subset(ds, ds$Stratum != "3.Usually notifies")

groups_12.stats <- data.frame(
  median = apply(groups_12[questions+11], MARGIN = 2, median),
  q25    = apply(groups_12[questions+11], MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x){quantile(x, probs = .25)}),
  q75    = apply(groups_12[questions+11], MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x){quantile(x, probs = .75)})
)

groups_12.stats$summary <-
  paste0(groups_12.stats$median, " [", 
         groups_12.stats$q25, ", ", 
         groups_12.stats$q75, "]")

# Prepare summary statistics for group 3
group_3   <- subset(ds, ds$Stratum == "3.Usually notifies")

group_3.stats <- data.frame(
  median = apply(group_3[questions+11], MARGIN = 2, median),
  q25    = apply(group_3[questions+11], MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x){quantile(x, probs = .25)}),
  q75    = apply(group_3[questions+11], MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x){quantile(x, probs = .75)})
)

group_3.stats$summary <-
  paste0(group_3.stats$median, " [", 
         group_3.stats$q25, ", ", 
         group_3.stats$q75, "]")

# Set new stratum variable with only 2 strata
ds$Stratum2 <- ifelse(ds$Stratum == "3.Usually notifies", "Regular notifiers", "Non-regular notifiers")


# Calculate p-values Mann-Whitney U test for each questions, comparing both groups
p.values <- sapply(seq_along(questions)+11, FUN = function(x){
  wilcox.test(ds[[x]] ~ ds$Stratum2)$p.value
  })
bonferroni <- p.values * 35
bonferroni <- ifelse(bonferroni > 1, 1, bonferroni)
bonferroni <- ifelse(bonferroni < 0.001, "< 0.001", format(round(bonferroni, 3), nsmall = 3))
p.values <- ifelse(p.values < 0.001, "< 0.001", format(round(p.values, 3), nsmall = 3))

# Aggregate results in a single table
result <- data.frame(
  Question = names(ds)[questions+11],
  Groups_12 = groups_12.stats$summary,
  Group_3 = group_3.stats$summary,
  P_value = p.values,
  Bonferroni = bonferroni
)

adjusted.names <- c(
  "Question",
  "Non-regular notifiers (median, [IQR]) n=175",
  "Regular notifiers (median, [IQR]) n=42",
  "Mann-Whitney U test",
  "Bonferroni correction"
)

result %>%
  kableExtra::kbl(
    align = c("l", "c", "c", "c", "c"), 
    col.names = adjusted.names,
    caption = 
      paste("Median, IQR and Mann-Whitney U test p-values between groups for each question.",
      "All participants from each group responded to all 35 questions.",
      # "Non-regular notifiers: n=175. Regular notifiers: n=42.",
      "With Bonferroni's correction, a p-value < 0.001 indicates a significant difference.",
      "Likert scale: 1 = Strongly disagree, 2 = Disagree,  3 = Neither,  4 = Agree,  5 = Strongly Agree."
      )
    ) %>%
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed")) %>%
  kableExtra:: kable_classic(full_width = T, html_font = "Cambria")

Association test for PE, CP, AS

From previous analysis, we pick questions with statistically significant difference regarding notification habits and evaluated further regarding:

  • PE: Professional Experience
  • CP: Specialist in Community Pharmacy
  • AS: Academic Studies

To determine whether there is a statistically significant association between these variables and questionsâ scores, we use Pearsonâs Chi-squared test.

# Define questions and variables to analyse
questions <-
  c("Q01. I am familiar with the Portuguese Pharmacovigilance System." 
    , "Q03. I am familiar with the Portal RAM for reporting suspected ADR."
    , "Q05. I am familiar with the update of the concept of ADR."
    , "Q13. I am careful to question the patient about ADR in my professional activity, assuming a proactive position in this issue."
    , "Q14. As a health professional, I have enough knowledge to identify a suspected ADR."
    , "Q23. I am reluctant to be judged by the report of a suspected ADR."
    )

variables <- 
  c("Professional Experience"
    , "Specialization in Community Pharmacy"
    , "Academic Degree"
    )

# Define combinations of 'variables' vs 'questions'
combinations <- expand.grid(variables, questions, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
names(combinations) <- c("variable", "question")
combinations$p.value <- NA

# Compute p.value for Chi.square test
for (i in 1:nrow(combinations)){
  chi <- 
    chisq.test(ds[[combinations$variable[i]]], 
               ds[[combinations$question[i]]])
  combinations$p.value[i] <- chi$p.value
}

# Aggregate values in a single table
table3 <- reshape2::dcast(data = combinations, 
     formula = question ~ variable, 
     fun.aggregate = function(x){sprintf("%.3f", sum(x))},
     value.var = 'p.value')
names(table3)[1] <- "Question"


# Print table
table3 %>%
  kableExtra::kbl(
    align = c("l", "c", "c","c"), 
    caption = paste("P-values for Pearson's Chi-squared test")
    ) %>%
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed")) %>%
  kableExtra:: kable_classic(full_width = T, html_font = "Cambria")
